
Läslig demo

   INFO  A guided primitive walkthrough
    This combined demo assembles the same focused examples that live under examples/ so the README GIFs and mage demo stay aligned.
    Use Läslig for ordinary CLI output, not command parsing or application logging.
    Run any focused example directly with go run ./examples/<name> --format human --style always, or use mage demo to assemble them all.


Section

  Use Section to start a new document region. The blocks that follow are indented under that heading until the next section begins.
  
  Section is the document-level primitive that gives the rest of the output clear ownership.

  Owned blocks
    what: Paragraphs, records, lists, tables, and panels inherit the active section indent.
    why: That default makes CLI output read more like a document than a stream of unrelated prints.


Next section

   INFO  Section boundaries reset ownership
    Starting another Section makes the boundary visible without requiring callers to manage indentation by hand.


Notice

   INFO  Use Notice for semantic user-facing diagnostics
    Notice is the default surface for info, success, warning, and error output that should stand out without turning into logging.
    When: validation feedback, partial success, next-step guidance, dependency checks, or release milestones.


Record

  Record
    what: One object or result rendered as labeled facts.
    when: Build metadata, artifact details, environment summaries.
    example: module github.com/evanmschultz/laslig


KV

  KV
    what    Compact aligned configuration or status.
    when    Resolved policy, flags, execution mode.
    format  human
    styled  true


List

  List
  - Grouped items  DEFAULT 
    when: Packages, tasks, phases, or capabilities that scan better than a table.
  - Badges stay lightweight  READY 
    why: Use a badge when a quick state is enough and a panel would be too heavy.
  - Detail fields add context  LIVE 
    what: Each item can carry labeled facts and still stay list-shaped.


Table

  Table
  ╭─────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  │ compare │ prefer when                               │
  │ ────────┼────────────────────────────────────────── │
  │ Table   │ column alignment matters across many rows │
  │ List    │ items are unordered and short             │
  │ Record  │ you are describing one object             │
  ╰─────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
  Use Table when comparison matters more than prose.


Panel

  ╭───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  │                                                                                                                   │
  │  Panel                                                                                                            │
  │                                                                                                                   │
  │  Use Panel for rationale, next steps, and larger callouts that should stand apart from the rest of the document.  │
  │                                                                                                                   │
  │  Panels are stronger than Paragraph and lighter than inventing a custom layout.                                   │
  │                                                                                                                   │
  ╰───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯


Paragraph

  Paragraph
  
  Use Paragraph for readable rationale, release context, and longer help text when a Notice or Panel would be too heavy.
  
  Paragraph is the simplest way to let a CLI explain itself in normal sentence-style text.


StatusLine

   SUCCESS  Use StatusLine for one compact semantic result (When: build ready, cache hit, package passed)


Spinner

  Use Spinner when long-running work might otherwise stay quiet for several seconds. Prefer StatusLine or Notice when the operation starts and finishes quickly enough that durable output is enough.
  
  This focused example falls back to stable start and finish status rows in plain, JSON, and non-interactive output.

  [RUNNING] Waiting for remote rollout
  [SUCCESS] Rollout ready


Markdown

  Use Markdown when your CLI already has release notes, changelog text, or generated help content to show.
  
  The block below is real terminal-rendered Markdown.

    # Release Notes                                                             
                                                                                
    ## Highlights                                                               
                                                                                
    • one renderer                                                              
    • three output surfaces                                                     
    • caller-owned logging                                                      


CodeBlock

  Use CodeBlock for commands, snippets, generated files, and config examples.
  
  The block below shows a Go snippet rendered through Glamour.

  ╭──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  │                                                                                      │
  │  Go snippet                                                                          │
  │                                                                                      │
  │                                                                                      │
  │      package main                                                                    │
  │                                                                                      │
  │      import "fmt"                                                                    │
  │                                                                                      │
  │      func main() {                                                                   │
  │          fmt.Println("hello from laslig")                                            │
  │      }                                                                               │
  │                                                                                      │
  │  Use CodeBlock when code should stay visibly distinct from prose.                    │
  │                                                                                      │
  ╰──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯


LogBlock

  Use LogBlock for selected stderr or log excerpts while the application keeps owning logging.
  
  The block below captures real charm/log output and renders it through Läslig.

  ╭────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
  │                                                                                        │
  │  Captured charm/log transcript                                                         │
  │                                                                                        │
  │  INFO demo: boot complete component=cache                                              │
  │  WARN demo: retry scheduled after=3s                                                   │
  │  ERRO demo: dependency missing name=git                                                │
  │                                                                                        │
  │  Use LogBlock for selected transcripts while the application keeps owning the logger.  │
  │                                                                                        │
  ╰────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯


gotestout

  Use gotestout for attractive, structured go test output when your task runner, CLI command, or Go helper behind make/just should keep owning process control.
  
  This focused example intentionally mixes passing, skipped, and failing test events plus one package build failure, and styled human terminals show gotestout's live activity block while the stream is still active.

   INFO  Mixed fixture demo
    The example command itself is expected to exit successfully so you can inspect the output shape.
    Use mage test for the real repository task-runner path.
